          "body": "Isaiah 3 opens with a divine *hinneh* — 'behold!' — the exclamation that demands the reader stop and look at what God is about to do. What He is about to do is specifically described as *removal* (*sur*): He will take away from Jerusalem and Judah both supply (*mishan*) and support (*mishenah*), the masculine and feminine forms of the same root exhausting the semantic range, signaling that every prop — physical and institutional — comes down. The catalog that follows in 3:2-3 is stunning in its breadth: ten categories of leadership, from the warrior and the judge to the expert artisan and the enchanter. Isaiah includes even the diviner and the skillful enchanter — not to endorse them, but to show how desperate a society becomes when God removes its competent leadership; they reach even to the occult for someone who might know what to do. The vacuum left by the removal of the competent produces the grotesque substitute of 3:4-7: capricious children in authority, social hierarchy inverted, and a scene so desperate that having a cloak is the sole qualification for leadership — and even that candidate refuses the office because he too has nothing. The refusal to lead in 3:7 is not cowardice but lucidity: the man with a cloak sees that the city is already ruins (*makhshelah*), a heap of rubble, and no healer can fix it. The pastoral note for any generation: when God removes the competent, the incompetent who replace them are not the problem — they are the announcement that God has begun His sentence."
