          "title": "The theological cause — defiance of the glorious presence (3:8-12)",
          "body": "Verse 8 inserts the theological explanation that verses 1-7 demand. The social chaos is not political accident; it has a moral root: Jerusalem has stumbled and Judah has fallen *because* their speech and their actions are against the Lord, to rebel against His glorious presence (*kavod*). The word *kavod* — glory, weight, honor — is the central theological category of Isaiah (cf. 6:3, the seraphim's cry; 40:5, the glory revealed). To rebel against the *kavod* is to assault the defining reality of the universe. Isaiah's analysis cuts beneath political dysfunction to the posture of the heart. Verse 9 specifies the symptom: the expression on their faces bears witness against them, and they display their sin like Sodom — not even concealing it. Isaiah does not describe spectacular apostasy; he describes the loss of shame. A society that has normalized its sin into public display has crossed a diagnostic threshold. The brief parenthesis of 3:10-11 interrupts the indictment to calibrate its justice: the righteous will eat the fruit of their actions; the wicked will be repaid. These two verses are the chapter's moral center of gravity, insisting that the judgment is not undifferentiated catastrophe but precise divine recompense. The double lament of 3:12 — 'O My people!' repeated — carries the pathos of a covenant God watching His own people being destroyed by the very guides He appointed to protect them. The lament is God's, not Isaiah's."
