          "title": "The courtroom — God rises to judge His own leaders (3:13-15)",
          "body": "The chapter's most dramatic moment is the scene shift of 3:13: *the Lord arises to contend* (*riv*). *Riv* is the Hebrew legal term for a covenant lawsuit — the prophetic genre scholars call the *rib* pattern, in which God acts as both plaintiff and judge in a formal prosecution of His covenant people (cf. Micah 6:1-5; Hosea 4:1-3). Isaiah uses the same pattern. God does not merely observe the injustice of Jerusalem's leaders; He stands in the court and enters the dispute. The accusation is specific and damning: 'It is you who have devoured the vineyard; the plunder of the poor is in your houses' (3:14). The vineyard metaphor will receive its fullest development in Isaiah 5:1-7, where Israel is explicitly named as the Lord's vineyard. Here the elders and princes who were meant to tend the vineyard have devoured it — and the evidence is in their homes. The cross-examination of 3:15 is the most direct speech in the chapter: 'What do you mean by crushing My people and grinding the face of the poor?' Declares the Lord God of Hosts. The verb *dakah* (to crush) and *tachan* (to grind) picture the poor as grain beneath a millstone — the image of total pulverization. God's use of 'My people' for the poor in 3:15 is the sentence's moral weight: these are *His* people the leaders are destroying. The elders and princes were stewards of what belonged to God; they have stolen from His household."
