          "body": "Verse 24 is the chapter's rhetorical climax, and it is structured by five repetitions of the word *tachat* — 'instead of.' Instead of fragrance, putrefaction. Instead of a belt, a rope. Instead of well-set hair, a plucked-out scalp. Instead of fine clothes, sackcloth. Instead of beauty, branding. Each reversal is calibrated to match what was displayed. The logic is talion — not arbitrary punishment but mirrored consequence. The women who adorned themselves to display their city's glory will wear the marks of the conquered and enslaved. The rope replaces the belt because their men will fall by the sword (3:25) — the rope is the prisoner's restraint. The baldness replaces the elaborate coiffure because the invader's hand has reached even that pride. Verse 26 closes the chapter not with the daughters of Zion but with the personified city itself: 'Her gates will lament and mourn, and deserted she will sit on the ground.' The gates — the locus of commerce, justice, and civic life in the ancient world — become mourners. The city that walked with its head held high sits in the posture of the bereaved and the conquered. There is no resolution in chapter 3; the reader must turn to chapter 4 for the first word of remnant hope. Isaiah is in no hurry to comfort a people who have not yet grasped the gravity of their condition."
