        "excerpt": "For behold, the Lord God of hosts is going to remove from Jerusalem and Judah both supply and support, the whole supply of bread and the whole supply of water.",
        "body": "The opening *ki hinneh* ('for behold') functions as a prosecutorial 'Exhibit A': everything described in 3:1-7 is the direct consequence of what chapter 2 announced — the Lord of Hosts has a day against all that is proud and lofty (2:12). Isaiah 3 translates that cosmic principle into domestic specifics. The first thing God removes is not the army or the treasury but *supply and support* — the staffs of bread and water (3:1). Physical sustenance and institutional competence fail simultaneously because God is withdrawing His providential hand from both.\n\nThe ten-category catalog of 3:2-3 is not a random list. It moves from military (mighty man, warrior) through judicial and prophetic (judge, prophet) through civic and technical (elder, captain of fifty, counselor, expert artisan) to the occult (diviner, skillful enchanter). The inclusion of the diviner and enchanter is not an endorsement of their legitimacy but an indicator of how desperate a society becomes when genuine prophetic and judicial leadership is removed — even the illegitimate substitutes will be missed. Childs (Isaiah, OTL) notes that the list represents every form of human competence on which a city might rely.\n\nThe vacuum produced by removal is the chapter's horror: capricious children (*taalul*, 3:4) — the word means willful, arbitrary, playing-games — appointed as princes. The social hierarchy inverts in 3:5: youth against elder, base against honorable. This is not merely unfortunate; in the ancient Near East, where social order was understood as participating in cosmic order, this inversion signals chaos — the undoing of God's own created structure for human community.\n\nThe scene of 3:6-7 is almost comic in its desperation: one man grabs his brother and says 'you have a cloak, so you lead us.' The only qualification is a surplus garment. The brother's response in 3:7 is the chapter's first explicit voice from the people: 'I will not be your healer' (*chavash* — to bind up, to heal). Even the man with resources refuses because he sees clearly what the city has become — ruins (*makhshelah*). The point Isaiah drives home: when God removes His scaffolding, no human improvisation can substitute for it. The search for a leader with a cloak is the sound of a covenant people who have lost access to the God who provides.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishan* and *mishenah* (3:1) share the root *shaan* (to lean, support) — the masculine and feminine forms exhausting the semantic range of 'prop.' The LXX renders them *iskhyn* and *ischun* (strength and mighty support). *Taalul* (3:4) — used only here and Ecclesiastes 1:2 — carries the sense of whim, randomness, play; capricious rulers in place of wise elders."
