        "body": "The genre shift in 3:13 is unmistakable to any reader of the prophets. Isaiah deploys the *rib* (covenant lawsuit) pattern — the formal legal proceeding in which YHWH acts as both the aggrieved party and the presiding judge. This pattern appears in Micah 6:1-5, Hosea 4:1-3, and Jeremiah 2:4-13, always structured around the formal accusation of covenant violation. Isaiah's version in 3:13-15 is unusually compressed: two verses of courtroom setting (God arises, stands, enters judgment) and one verse of direct accusation.\n\nThe accusation is devastatingly specific. The elders and princes have 'devoured the vineyard' (3:14). The vineyard is already a loaded image in Isaiah — in 5:1-7 it becomes the full extended metaphor for Israel, the Lord's carefully planted and tended heritage. Here in chapter 3 the leaders who were appointed to tend the vineyard have eaten it instead. The plunder of the poor (*gezelah me-ani*, 3:14) — stolen property from the afflicted — is located not in their fields but in their houses. The evidence of injustice has been brought inside and domesticated. This is systemic exploitation, not occasional corruption.\n\nThe cross-examination of 3:15 is the most direct speech in the chapter and the most emotionally charged: 'What do you mean by crushing My people and grinding the face of the poor?' The two verbs — *dakah* (to crush, to be crushed flat) and *tachan* (to grind, as grain in a mill) — picture the poor as material to be processed. Spurgeon (Treasury of David, on Psalm 72) connects this language to the Psalmic tradition of God as the defender of the poor; what the elders have done to the poor is precisely what God's king was meant to prevent. The divine title at the end — 'declares the Lord God of Hosts' — functions as the judge's gavel: the verdict is pronounced by the one who commands every army in creation.\n\nThe theological import for canonical reading is substantial. This passage stands behind Jesus's own *rib* against Jerusalem's leaders (Matthew 23) and James's prosecution of the rich who have defrauded their workers (James 5:1-6). God's identification of the exploited poor as 'My people' (3:15) is a consistent canonical thread: the poor are His particular ward, and those who crush them assault the household of heaven.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Riv* (contend, 3:13) — the technical covenant-lawsuit term. *Natsav* (arises, stands firm, 3:13) — the same word used of an officer rising to take a formal position of authority. *Dakah* (crush, 3:15) — used elsewhere of shattering to pieces (Psalm 44:19); *tachan* (grind, 3:15) — the millstone verb, used of grinding grain to powder. Together they are the most violent verbs in the chapter."
